Impact of The Malicious Clientâ€™s Proportion.
We first assess the effectiveness of our method in both IID and non-IID cross-silo FL system with only 101010% of clients compromised, as shown in TableÂ IV. This setup revealed that all baseline model poisoning attacks yield lower error rates on the global model compared with scenarios with 202020% compromised clients. While the increase in error rates was less than those in the 202020% compromised client scenario, our method still effectively raises the global modelâ€™s error rates in 252525/262626 out of 282828 cases (IID/non-IID setting). The maximum increase in error rates reached 0.4030.4030.403, with an average increase of 0.1440.1440.144. This average is notably higher (>222x higher) than the error rates observed in attack-free FL conditions. Specifically, our method help sign-flipping/Trim/Krum/Min-Max attacks achieve an average error rate increase of 0.1330.1330.133/0.0940.0940.094/0.1360.1360.136/0.2090.2090.209. More detailed results are presented in AppendixÂ G.

Impact of The Datasets and Model Architectures.
Following the evaluation with the Fashion-MNIST dataset, we test our method on the MNIST and CIFAR-10 dataset, employing the four-layer CNN model and the AlexNet model to further verify our methodâ€™s generality across different datasets.
The collective results show that our method performs even better with larger datasets or more complex machine learning models. This trend confirms the generality of our method by revealing its capability to maintain consistent performance enhancements regardless of the dataset or model complexity involved. Specifically, our method help all the four baseline attacks bypass all the nine baselines on CIFAR-10 dataset, achieving 0.2880.2880.288 error rate increase on average, presented in TableÂ V. More detailed results on MNIST dataset are shown in AppendixÂ E.
The detailed results on MNIST and CIFAR-10 dataset are presented in TableÂ IX (MNIST dataset) and TableÂ V (CIFAR-10 dataset), respectively.

These tests were conducted under both IID and non-IID data environments. DSTrust effectively neutralizes the four baseline poisoning attacks when our method is not applied, highlighting its robustness as a defense mechanism. Despite DSTrustâ€™s integration of both cosine similarity and distance metrics in its defense strategy, it fails to counteract the augmented attacks when our method is employed. Notably, our method achieves a maximum error rate increase of 0.5210.5210.521, and an average error rate increase of 0.1730.1730.173 across all 888 test scenarios. These results demonstrate that merely understanding the adjustment strategies of our method, and subsequently integrating corresponding defense metrics, does not fundamentally negate the effectiveness of our method. Despite the adaptive defenseâ€™s attempt to incorporate both cosine similarity and distance metrics into DSTrust, it remains insufficient to thwart the enhanced capabilities of our method.
